The article discusses the introduction of an Assault Weapons and High-Capacity Magazine Ban in the Senate, along with legislation to raise the age to purchase them to 21. The author mentions that in the 10 years that the Assault Weapons Ban was in effect, mass shootings decreased, but after it expired in 2004, mass shootings tripled. The author urges Congress to act quickly and deliver the Assault Weapons Ban to their desk, stating that the majority of the American people support this action to ensure the safety of children, communities, and the nation.